title: MATEIN Travel Laptop Backpack, Business Anti Theft Slim Durable Laptops Backpack with USB Charging Port, Water Resistant College School Computer Bag Gift for Men & Women Fits 15.6 Inch Notebook, Grey
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Amazingly well made and durable yet fairly light.', 'author': 'Ernie J', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I bought 2 of these backpacks. Only layout change I'd make was putting a pocket on the other side of the laptop compartment, seems like a waste of space there. Love the hooks on the straps. With my old backpack I had a Caribeener Clip on the front I used to keep a travel day pack on so when I walked it'd be on the back. I was always nervous about it falling off (did once) I was happy to see these hooks on the straps. Wished on the 3rd zipper had it too, as I'm sure people would like to secure stuff there also. One thing I did notice was the zippers and straps are def weaker then my old backpack. They're def way easier to open, doesn't feel as secure to my old one. The straps seem easier to come loose too, one did when I was on my flight back home and I went to grab it to put it on getting off. It's possible I loosened it during the flight, so not totally blaming the company there.The next con is quality control with this company. The first backpack I got the USB charging port was completely blocked off by plastic (as shown in one of the pics). Back it went for a replacement. The second one I got the port did work, but was def finicky plugging in the cable to it. There was a sale so back this went and got a third one, and finally this one was perfect. If they improve that, I'd bring up my rating to a 4.5/5 for this backpack. As it stands, still a 4/5.While traveling I put down this backpack kinda hard on hardwood floors. The next time I turned on my MacBook Air M1 (2020) I had a bleeding blob screen defect on my laptop. I don't think that would have happened with my old backpack. Opened it a couple days later, and the blob def changed and is now for the most part gone. title: MATEIN Backpack for Men, Extra Large Laptop Backpack with USB Port, Travel Backpacks for Women, Anti Theft College Computer Bag Water Resistant TSA Business Work Rucksack Fit 17 Inch Notebook, Black
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars OMG I love this bag!', 'author': 'Moomtaz', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I upgraded to this bag from an OGIO bag. I liked the OGIO but it was impractical with four divided sections making each section too tight for actual stuffing. I bought a larger 40L Matien travel bag and thought this would make a great daily commuting bag, but it looks like this bag is all that I need. This bag has 1 large pouch that has two mesh pouches inside and a battery bank pocket. That puts nothing in your way of actually carrying a ton of stuff. On the front is a gear pouch for stuffing all of your accessory cables and an organization pouch. The two side zip up pockets are a bonus with water bottle holders. The back pocket holds your laptop and files and the anti-theft pouch in the back with the luggage strap. Perfect for traveling. The handle is soft and cushy so we will see how it holds up over time. The bag stands up by itself without falling over. This thing is awesome!In the pictures there are 2 pairs of jeans, 4 underwear and socks, three shirts and a set of pajamas. 7 USBC cords, 4 port USB charger, 1 mac charger, and a SSD drive. One Emirates travel bag full of supplies. One battery power bank. One 15" Macbook pro. One Boox Max3. The 2 side pockets are Empty.The one thing I didn\'t like was the power bank pouch. You can see in the picture that it has no elastic whereas the 40L does and just adds that smidge of reassurance that it\'s not going to be flopping around. Other than that I have no complaints about this bag.This is a TSA travel bag which means that the laptop part is supposed to open and you\'re supposed to sail through the checkpoint. I\'ve never experienced where this works, if you can tell me how to do this great, the agents always tell me to remove my laptops and place them in their own bin so to me this is a wasted feature. If you know how to do this in according to how it\'s supposed to work let me know.Update: 7.17Just returned from my trip to Tanzania and this bag was literally all I needed. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars 3+ years later, this backpack is still going strong', 'author': 'Elle', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I\'ve had this backpack since 2019 and I\'ve taken it to quite a few places. The first time I ordered it, the zippers immediately broke so I was sent a replacement, but I haven\'t had any issues since. The zippers, mesh, pockets, etc. all are running very smoothly, even though I\'m a chronic over-stuffer.In the beginning of 2019, I packed this backpack and took it to Europe for about three months. It was my only luggage as I traveled cross-country via bus and plane, hostels and hotel rooms. Conclusion? This thing is HEFTY and can fit a lot of stuff.Over the years, I\'ve used it as my carry-on luggage for what amounts to maybe 30-40 trips now, and I also use it for short local weeklong trips, too. When it\'s overstuffed, it\'s too big to fit below the seat, so I mostly used it as an upper bin bag. It\'s slammed along the bottom of over a dozen bus carriages, trekked through wet, humid, and dry conditions, and it still looks great. I\'d say it\'s even stretched out a few inches over the years.Here are a few things you should know:- I wore this as I walked the misty, rainy streets of Edinburgh and the clothes inside remained dry.- I\'ve had to run to catch planes in-between quick layovers, sweating as I raced to catch my plane, and the straps have excellent wicking capabilities, because it\'s never smelled.There is a clamshell backing compartment that opens completely flat which is great for electronics. For me, it fits all of this:-12.5" Dell laptop-11" MacBook with padded holder-A paperback book or 1-2 magazines- 8" tablet readerI can also sometimes cram my laptop fan, but sometimes not, if I pack too many clothes.That compartment is about 2.5" W x 17"H closed. Frankly, it doesn\'t have a lot of give, so I try not to add additional items to that side.-There are two pockets in the side that have zippers, usually I add water bottles here, but you could also add shoes or dirty socks inside the zippered areas.-The largest compartment measures around 6.5" W x 16" H, though it has stretched out over the years.Here\'s a sample of clothes I can pack here when rolled them; rolled and wrapped a measuring tape around each piece of clothing to get the diameter, then measured the height (before I squish it all together):-1 pair of sweat pants 10" x 4"-1 sweater 9" x 3.5"-2 pairs of pants, one at 11" x 4" and 10" x 3.5"-1 sweater dress at 10" x 6"-1 pair of tights at 5" x 3"-1 sweater at 11" x 6"Then a packing cube with various undergarments (3 pairs of socks, 3 pairs of underwear) and two long-sleeved shirts at 11" x 4.5"-And that leaves an empty space for more at 7" x 5" I put a few pairs of socks and a Google Nest in, but it\'s still not packed snuggly.-Then there\'s an additional flap, where I usually add a small toiletry bag with soap, shampoo, toothbrush/toothpaste, etc.-There\'s another small clamshell pocket where you can put pens, and there\'s a key ring so your keys don\'t get lost inside your bag.-There\'s an additional zippered pocket where I put my passport and extra TSA locks.There are straps on each side that I\'ve pre-measured out so that if I want, I can fit the bag under a domestic airline seat. With all of the above mentioned, there\'s room to spare for a few more things.Instead of adding toiletries to the end pockets, they would fit at the top of the pack and make it nice and snug. Enough clothes for 3-7 days, easily, depending on what you pack.-And to the handle, I\'ll usually wrap a scarf and neck pillow, or a jacket for the flight.And here are your caveats:-The more you pack those two deep pockets (clothes and electronics), the less space you\'ll have to pack anything else in the extra pockets.-If packing for underneath a seat, you can\'t have much in any of the other pockets or side mesh holders.-The bag is designed so you have to put some things in each of the two large compartments, you can\'t just fill up the larger one with clothes. It will gap and you\'ll find you\'re wasting space.-The straps are very thick and not particularly comfortable, especially when the bag is full, for a smaller frame like mine (5\'3").Recently, I\'m entertaining the idea of switching out this backpack because of my own back lol. I need to downgrade to a rolling checked bag and get a smaller, lightweight backpack for my electronics since I WFH now and need to bring a bit more gear than I used to. But I continue to take this pack when I\'m spending the night somewhere for a few days, and I would definitely consider taking it on a short trip if I didn\'t need to bring my work equipment.Maybe I\'ll come back in a couple of years and let you know how I\'m using it at that time!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 23, 2021', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Large Durable Backpack', 'author': 'Bubba Kahana', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'This backpack is oversized and durable. My daughter loves all the roomy separated areas for organizing her school work and chrome book. This pack will be extra handy for traveling as it opens up to lay flat for scanning at airports.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 29, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Seems like a good bag', 'author': 'Bluecowgirl', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'We just got this in the mail and I packed it last night and my husband is flying right now with it, will update after his trip as he is going through two airports to get to his destination, and then two more to get back after a short cruise it looks really sturdy. Just don’t forget you have to buy your own power pack to charge stuff up but otherwise it looks really cool and useful ten billion pockets so you just have to remember where you put what.March 2024 if I don’t respond back it means I forgot to update this as the backpack did wonderful on his trip', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 3, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Zipper broke and came unstitched. *2nd Updated!', 'author': 'ASHLEY', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Backpack with tons of room. I would have given 5 stars but 2 weeks after my daughter started using it, 1 of the zippers broke and came unstitched.*UPDATE: seller reached out and offered to replace the backpack due to zipper issues. We received the replacement within 3 days. They were very nice and understanding thru the communication. Even with the small issue will still use this company in the future. My son has had no issues with his that he received.Update #2: originals order was 2 backpacks, my sons lasted 2 months before the rubber grip over the handle started ripping apart. The cable is sturdy but hard to use without the cover.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 16, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Durable & Versatile', 'author': 'Paul L.', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'Got this in September. These past 3 months I\'ve used it for trans-Atlantic flight to England, trans-Pacific flight to Japan, 7 day trip to Disney in Orlando as well as a couple road trips for racing events. So far, it has held up nicely. Had up to 35-40lbs worth of gear in it with no issues.Pro\'s: Durable. Comfortable. LOTS of storage compartments & they are easy to get to & use. Has pass-through slots for cables from your battery to your device. Decent enough padding for your electronics. Multiple pockets of varying sizes for different needs. Bottle holders work great & have straps to clip taller bottles in. Side straps can be used to buckle in hoodies or jackets/wind breakers. carry handle is very stiff & solid - hung loaded bag from it on a hook with no issues.Con\'s: TOO many pockets - easy to lose track of WHERE you put stuff! Lots of zippers - would be nice if they were colored (the black zippers blend in w the black backpack making it hard to find in low light). The 2 vertical pockets on either side near the bottle holders are narrow - if you have large hands, it\'s hard to get down to the bottom for small items. Would be really nice if it had a chest strap to connect the 2 shoulder harnesses - have that on my old backpack & really like that feature, especially for heavier loads. Would be a "5-Star" review if not for those last 2 items.All in all, a really good travel backpack for the money.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 15, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Big, waterproof, reliable', 'author': 'maddie', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I bought this backpack before embarking on a 2 year masters degree which requires me to travel across Europe every few months. I bought it bc I am not capable of packing lightly and wanted a big backpack w many pockets that I can shove full as a carry on- and it works perfectly for that.However I decided to write this review bc I recently moved to Bergen Norway. It rains every single day. This has also become my university backpack, although it’s a bit big to just carry my laptop and water bottle and snacks.. but I don’t have another one. Anyway, it holds up so well in the rain. Granted I haven’t had it long, but my laptops and books and everything else stay dry inside even when the rain soaks through my jacket and sweater..There’s no signs of wear yet and I’ve used it daily for months. When I shove it full for travel, I REALLY shove it full, and no signs of wear from that either. When it’s only carrying a few things, I like that I can cinch it up with side straps / clips so the empty pockets don’t gape out and it makes the whole thing slimmer.Overall I’m very impressed w the quality considering it’s from Amazon and not some name brand, which would be much more expensive. Definitely recommend this backpack, it’s a huge bargain but performs like any other high quality name brand backpack. Very happy with it.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 31, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great travel bag', 'author': 'D Inzunza', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Bought this bag for travel and so far so good. Plenty of compartments to allow for quick access to things when traveling. Only downside is the side mesh is pretty small and doesn’t hold a large water bottle. Will hold a small one but my wife and I tend to bring a larger bottle for the both of us and it won’t accommodate. Otherwise a good overall bag.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 26, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Thee backpack!', 'author': 'Miguel Ramos', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'One great backpack. Large capacity, stylish and comfortable. I recommend it.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 18, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars So. Much. Room.', 'author': 'Tess Hietbrink', 'rating': 4, 'content': "This bag has INSANE space. I packed a ps5, portable monitor, 65% keyboard, wireless mouse, change of clothes, cables, chargers, 2 battery banks, keys, misc electronics, a Steam Deck and MULTIPLE controllers (Gamecube, 2 PS5, Switch) into this thing and it all fit pretty comfortably. Insane. I have back problems but even with all these things packed in with how it distributes the weight with the different sized pockets and the great shoulder straps, I had very little issues carrying this thing. Would be much better with a chest strap to help even more, but otherwise this thing is amazing.No issues with the security lock and I love having that option there for the bigger electronics pocket. I really love having the USB pass-through that lets me keep my battery bank in the inside pocket to charge my phone from the bag itself without having to dig through it. When I store it I hang it from the handle on the top and I was worried about that tearing, but it's been hanging for 3 months with some light cables and books in it and all that's happened is the handle warped a bit. No fraying on the fabric or signs of damage.I just love this bag so much and I hope it lasts me a long time. Fingers crossed!!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 13, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars I love it.', 'author': 'Moo', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I took a 6-day trip to the Pacific Northwest. Considering the weather this time of year, I had to pack multiple layers. I packed 5 base layer sets, 6 pairs of socks, three pairs of pants, a set of rain gear, 4 beanies, snacks, my water jug, and a spare pair of boots with room to spare. It fits easily into the overhead bins as well.I'm taking a 10 day trip to the UK this summer, I am fully confident I will be able to use this pack instead of a suitcase for the trek.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 4, 2024', 'is_verified': True}]

title: Laptop Backpack,Business Travel Anti Theft Slim Durable Laptops Backpack with USB Charging Port,Water Resistant College Computer Bag for Women & Men Fits 15.6 Inch Laptop and Notebook - Black
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Amazing!', 'author': 'Nox', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I\'m absolutely loving this backpack! I am so glad I found this one. It is far more lightweight than my Nordace one, plenty of pockets and zippers for organization, inner pockets and a back pocket for security (I personally keep my wallet in an inner zipper pocket since the back pocket is a wee bit small). It also looks exactly like the picture (which is very exciting to me). Here\'s a bit of a breakdown:Pros: - Large laptop pocket (fits my 16" laptop) - Lots of pockets - Against-the-back security pocket - Very breathable - Very light - Feels high quality and durable - 3 bottle-holder pockets (2 outside, 1 inside) - USB charging for portable batteries - Strap for attaching to luggage - WaterproofCons: - Likely won\'t hold larger items like textbooks (at least, it doesn\'t hold my large ones) - Security pocket is small - Doesn\'t have 2 laptop pockets - VERY tight outer bottle holder pocketsI, personally, got this for both work and school so I can carry both laptops together. It doesn\'t have 2 laptop pockets, but the one that it does is MASSIVE. The strap is actually loose even after putting both laptops into it so it can easily fit larger laptops. I went on a work trip and it was perfect. Half the time, I forget how much stuff I have in my backpack because of how light it is and how well it disperses the weight. I also appreciate that it\'s slim. My previous backpacks have always been bulky and I always felt awkward while trying to squeeze down the aisles of a plane to get to my seat, but it wasn\'t a problem this time. I do wish the outer bottle holder pockets were a little looser and larger so that I can fit my larger water bottle into them, but it isn\'t too big of a deal for me since I like to carry my bottle for the most part.Overall, this backpack is AMAZING for the price that it\'s set at and I hope more people find this. A spot for a laptop if you utilize it.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 6, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Shoulder and waist straps are short', 'author': 'Mike', 'rating': 4, 'content': "My reveiw is:Right out of the box and am packing it for the first time.First of all, I need this pack style for my job.I work out door all during my shift and I need to live out of this pack.I thought I'd give this pack a try to consolodate what I now carry (two bags) into one convenient back pack.No can do, but that it not the pack's fault. That is mine..... I like all the comforts of home with me during the day.I was looking for something compactful without looking like I was going trekking for 5 days.The material is sturdy. Exactly what I'd expect from such a pack.The Zippers to the two main compartments may not hold up well over time if you like to over stuff your pack.I've noted it and will be careful with them and try not to over pack the bag.My main disappointment is with the length of the shoulder straps and the waist strap.I am a big barrel chested guy. The shoulder straps are a struggle to get over my shoulders.If I have to wear an overcoat in really cold weather, the bag won't fit over my shoulders.Likewise, the waist straps won't fit around my size 48 belly....I will have to find some extenders to attach to the straps to make use of the straps on this bag.Once I am at work, I don't have to wear the bag.I can set it down on my workspace and have it handy when I need it.But I still need to carry a second but smaller ditty bagMy reason for the 3 stars for comfort are due to the shorted length of the straps.This was my only disappointment.Finally, I was attracted to the price of this item and thought to give it a try.Maybe I was a bit harsh in my review for such an inexpensive item, but as a recreational bag, this bag is better than okay. If you need to pack for a light weighted walk in the woods, this bag will accommodate you nicely.____________________________________________________Updated Review: Feb 29th.One week into using this bag, the only thing I find a problem for me is the length of the shoulder straps and thw waist belt. I am a bulky guy and the strap lengths are much too short for comfort. I am choking from the combined weight and shortness of the shoulder straps and the chest straps, forget about them. No use to me.The waist belt causes the bag to hang on me causing me more choking.Finding strap accessories wasn't easy at first.I searched YouTube and got lucky finding a solution for the shoulder straps buying a kit from Liberty Mountain Products; they sell lots of climbing gear.Then I searched Amazon for Liberty Mountain and found plenty of strap accessories.Now I have a complete solution for the shortness of shoulder and waist straps.Why put out a product with these kinds of issues in the first place ?At least produce some accessory straps to buy...Why make me search for a solution.I have plenty of other things on my mind....But now I have a pack that will serve me well for my limited needs from this pack.As a piece of luggage for everyday use or a gentle day walk in the woods... this pack is fine.Were in my 20's again winter camping in extreme conditions..... nope... I would not bet my life on a $35 bag.___________________________________________________________It's now September and I am still using this molle bag.By now I have tricked out the bag with accessory pouches and storage attachments.I am reasonably satisfied with this pack after having tricked it out with useful attachments.If I were to buy this system all over again, and I might for my motorcycle riding, a pack with a more supportive waist belt would be a priority for me. The entire weight of this pack fully loaded hangs on your shoulders instead of the weight being distribution around your waist allowing your chest to expand and breathe with you._______________________Sept 12th, 2020I only carry this bag from my car to my building to my work vehicle.I've got it tricked out with extra attachments to separate out my gear and lunch for easy access.I always pack more than what I need for the day, but during the week, I will access all compartments.Because I need to carry this bag short distances, it works for this purpose.And once inside my work vehicle, this bag is perfect; it suits the purpose for my 8 hour shift. (or double shift)If I were doing overnight in the woods on the ground camping, this bag is NOT for that purpose.You would be better off with a bag with a waist belt that centers the load over your hips and OFF your shoulders.At minimum, a rucksack with a decent hip padded waist belt.This bag is okay for lightweight day hiking;But I'd still opt for a bag with a padded waist belt that can center your load over your hips.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 22, 2020', 'is_verified': True}]

reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars OMG I love this bag!', 'author': 'Moomtaz', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I upgraded to this bag from an OGIO bag. On the front is a gear pouch for stuffing all of your accessory cables and an organization pouch. The two side zip up pockets are a bonus with water bottle holders. The back pocket holds your laptop and files and the anti-theft pouch in the back with the luggage strap. Perfect for traveling. The handle is soft and cushy so we will see how it holds up over time. The bag stands up by itself without falling over. This thing is awesome!In the pictures there are 2 pairs of jeans, 4 underwear and socks, three shirts and a set of pajamas. 7 USBC cords, 4 port USB charger, 1 mac charger, and a SSD drive. One Emirates travel bag full of supplies. One battery power bank. One 15" Macbook pro. One Boox Max3. The 2 side pockets are Empty.The one thing I didn\'t like was the power bank pouch. You can see in the picture that it has no elastic whereas the 40L does and just adds that smidge of reassurance that it\'s not going to be flopping around. This backpack has it all – style, functionality, and the TSA-friendly design that makes my globetrotting adventures a breeze. Strap in, because I'm about to share why this backpack is a must-have for any traveler.First things first, let's talk about organization. This backpack is a master of compartmentalization. With multiple pockets and compartments, it's like having a personal assistant to keep everything in order. The dedicated laptop sleeve is padded and snug, ensuring that my tech gear stays safe and secure throughout my journey. Plus, the thoughtful placement of pockets makes it effortless to access my essentials on the go. No more rummaging through a chaotic abyss of items—I'm a pro at finding what I need in seconds!One of the standout features of this backpack is its TSA-friendly design. Gone are the days of struggling to remove my laptop during airport security checks. The MATEIN backpack opens flat, allowing me to breeze through checkpoints with ease. It's like a magic trick that never fails to impress fellow travelers and security personnel. Not to mention, the time and stress it saves me are priceless. I've never felt so sophisticated while navigating airport security!When it comes to comfort, the MATEIN backpack gets top marks. The padded shoulder straps and back panel provide excellent support, even during long journeys. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars My honest review', 'author': 'Larry Stinson', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I recently purchased the Himal Military Tactical Backpack, looking for a durable and spacious pack for outdoor adventures and travel. Overall, I'm impressed with its quality and functionality. The backpack is well-built with sturdy materials and reinforced stitching, giving me confidence that it can withstand rugged use. The 40L capacity provides ample space for all my gear, making it suitable for multi-day hikes or as a travel backpack. The Molle system allows for additional customization and attachment of extra pouches or gear. Plus, the numerous compartments and pockets help keep everything organized and easily accessible. However, I did find the shoulder straps to be a bit uncomfortable during extended wear, lacking sufficient padding for heavier loads. Additionally, while the backpack is water-resistant, it's not fully waterproof, so I would recommend using a rain cover in wet conditions. Despite these minor drawbacks, the Himal Military Tactical Backpack offers excellent value for its price, providing durability, versatility, and ample storage for outdoor enthusiasts and travelers alike.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 27, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Fits EVERYTHING- GREAT SISSY BAR MOTORCYCLE BAG!', 'author': 'Olivia Twisted', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Fits EVERYTHING- GREAT SISSY BAR MOTORCYCLE BAG! This backpack is AMAZING! It fits my 17” laptop PERFECTLY. AND my lunch, a spare set of clothes, four bottles of water, some personal essentials, AND a spare helmet if I don’t want to wear the full face helmet. I use this bag for my daily commute on the sissy bar of my motorcycle. It is sturdy and tough. The straps are super comfy for carrying around and on hikes and treks everywhere. LOTS of ROOM! (See Photos) The tactical loop on the outside allows me to ADD more bags to this backpack for long tours on the road. I modified the back water pouch to fit on the sissy bar by splitting the bottom seam VERY CAREFULLY. I then reinforced the bottom of the sleeve with some hand stitching and seam tape. I attach the bag to my motorcycle with the sissy bar sleeve and a ROK Strap for safety. This is the best backpack by far compared to other “better brands” and it is economical. This is the bag for me. Ordering a few more for other purposes as well. GREAT PRODUCT! So happy!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States September 1, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars A-M-A-Z-I-N-G', 'author': 'va2jazy', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I purchased this for my middle school daughter because I wen through 4 backpacks last year for her 7th grade year. The books and supplies along with laptop weighs 51lbs (I weighed her bookbag). I bought EXPENSIVE backpacks last year and ALL ripped. We are 3 weeks into school and this backpack is amazing! Comfortable, many pockets, extra large size... I AM TRULY HAPPY WITH MY PURCHASE AND WILL BE BUYING ONE FOR EACH YEAR OF SCHOOL', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States August 2, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Extremely Happy', 'author': 'CV3MOM', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Excellent durability and quality material! Surprised with our purchase.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 23, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Good for travel.', 'author': 'J Don', 'rating': 4, 'content': "This bag is well made with plenty of space. Zippers seem sturdy.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 19, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Quite pleased with first impressions', 'author': 'Amazon Customer', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I wanted a backpack for my laptop and it does fit a laptop with a 17 inch screen. The computer does stick out passed the padding area, but it still fits in the backpack. There is padding on both sides of the laptop but no harder padding, which is okay. I got it on sale for less than $25 and I’d say it’s still a good deal for just under $30. Considering if I went to a store that claims it has the “best buys” or “targeted” a different store, one could easily pay upwards to $35 to $50 for a computer backpack with potentially less features. It’s basically for safekeeping for my laptop and I don’t plan on hauling it around everywhere. The built in lock is a nice feature and a deterrent for unauthorized use. I like the other features. Overall, I am pleased with my purchase and I recommend it for the price. It seems that the reviewer’s that I had bad experiences received defective ones. Hopefully, mine holds out for my needs. Although, for the price, I can see how there may be some lemons that get through quality control.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 4, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars The perfect size!', 'author': 'Victoria Baker', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I had the 15" version of this, which was great as my work laptop bag, but not all that great for travel- it just didn\'t hold much. But I can tell it\'s going to be great for travel to carry my laptop, a few files and essentials for on the plane. Super happy with this purchase so far.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 17, 2024', 'is_verified': True}]

title: Lenovo Laptop Backpack B210, 15.6-Inch Laptop/Tablet, Durable, Water-Repellent, Lightweight, Clean Design, Sleek for Travel, Business Casual or College, GX40Q17225, Black
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Excellent backpack', 'author': 'Tenor NYC', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I really like this backpack. Suits my need perfectly. It's stylish and feels substantial and comfortable. Perfect size. Not bulky and does sag. Very pleased with this purchase. No bottle holder, not an issue for me but some may consider that necessary.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 20, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Techie on the Go: A Review of the Lenovo Laptop Backpack B210', 'author': 'Amazon Customer', 'rating': 5, 'content': "As a tech enthusiast, I'm always on the lookout for gear that blends functionality and style. The Lenovo Laptop Backpack B210 in black caught my eye with its sleek design and promise of water-repellent durability. After putting it through its paces for a few weeks, here's my honest review:First Impressions:Look and Feel: This backpack strikes a great balance between professional and casual. The clean lines and black color make it suitable for both office commutes and co-working spaces. The water-repellent fabric feels sturdy and looks sharp, and the overall construction seems solid.Size and Weight: The B210 is surprisingly lightweight, even when fully loaded with my 15.6-inch laptop, charger, and tech accessories. The size is perfect for everyday use, offering enough space without feeling bulky.Functionality:Compartments and Organization: The dedicated laptop compartment is well-padded and fits my device snugly. The main compartment is roomy enough for books, notebooks, and my lunch bag. The multiple internal pockets keep smaller items like cords and chargers organized, and the side mesh pockets are handy for water bottles or quick-access items.Carrying Comfort: The adjustable, padded shoulder straps distribute weight evenly, making it comfortable to carry even for extended periods. The back panel is also padded for added comfort.Durability:Water Resistance: I haven't been caught in a downpour yet, but the water-repellent fabric has held up well against light spills and splashes. It gives me peace of mind knowing my tech is protected during unexpected weather changes.Construction: The stitching and materials seem high-quality and durable. I haven't experienced any rips or tears during my use, and I expect this backpack to last for a long time.Overall Impression:The Lenovo Laptop Backpack B210 is a solid choice for tech enthusiasts like myself who value both style and functionality. It's lightweight, comfortable to carry, and offers ample storage for everyday essentials. The water-resistant fabric and durable construction provide peace of mind, and the clean design makes it suitable for various settings. For the price, it's a great value proposition, and I would definitely recommend it to anyone looking for a reliable and stylish backpack for their tech gear.-Value: I believe the B210 offers good value for its price point. It's not the cheapest backpack on the market, but the quality and features justify the cost.-Durability: Based on my initial impressions and the quality of materials, I expect this backpack to be durable and long-lasting.-Usability: The B210 is easy to use and navigate, with well-organized compartments and comfortable carrying straps.-Innovation: While not groundbreaking, the backpack incorporates thoughtful features like water-resistant fabric and a padded laptop compartment, making it a practical choice for tech users.-Overall: I would recommend the Lenovo Laptop Backpack B210 to anyone looking for a stylish, functional, and durable backpack for their everyday tech essentials.I hope this review is helpful! Please let me know if you have any questions.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 2, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars For the price, excellent choice!', 'author': 'Amazon Customer', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Worth the money. Good space, waterproof, super lightweigth.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 1, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Great basic, simple, no-frills bag.', 'author': 'JLM', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'This is better than you would expect for an $18 backpack, but you aren\'t going to get $80 worth of features. I\'ve been using this bag about a month now on daily subway travel, and while I\'m happy with it, I know it probably won\'t be a have-it-forever bag, which is fine by me. I\'ve never had a subway commute before, so I just wanted to get a sense of whether I liked using a backpack or whether I needed to invest in a better shoulder bag, and for that, this fits the bill.I\'m a woman of fairly small stature, 5\'2 and petite all around, so I didn\'t want to feel like I was back in my middle school days with a backpack that made me look like an ersatz turtle clomping down the street. I wanted something fairly professional, slim, and with a little bit of something, not just another black backpack. And obviously, for a trial run, I didn\'t want to spend a lot.This bag in the blue color fit the bill. It\'s a very nice neutral blue, like a pair of jeans, so it goes with nearly everything. It doesn\'t appear to be showing dirt or grime yet, which is nice. The zippers are fairly high quality considering; I haven\'t had any issues with them sticking or getting jammed. The fabric appears to be a decent quality nylon and is fairly water resistant. I wouldn\'t call it waterproof, nor would I trust my computer in there in a heavy rainstorm without an umbrella or putting it under a jacket, but for a drizzle or minor shower everything inside has stayed dry.The lining is cheap nylon. Full stop. It will tear in time. But it\'s nicely designed, with an integrated front pocket big enough for a large-ish smart phone, car keys, metro card, chapstick, and a few other sundries without a problem. It\'s a deep pocket with a shallower "shelf" pocket, which is nice to keep the smaller things accessible. The main compartment is roomier than you\'d think, even with a 15 inch laptop inside. The laptop compartment is not very well padded, kind of not padded at all almost, but it\'s roomy. There are also two smaller pockets along the front of the main compartment, big enough for a cell phone, pens, that sort of stuff. And then the deep well easily fits a small umbrella, a Tupperware for lunch, a large-ish water bottle, and a large wallet, even with a laptop inside. I can also cram a packable rain jacket in there without trouble, though it starts to look kind of stuffed at that point.Don\'t labor under any delusions that this thing is going to magically distribute weight or anything like that. It won\'t. You are carrying your load on your shoulders. It\'s not super well padded, it\'s not super breathable. If you\'re looking for a bag that\'s going to be at your side 24/7 around the country or around the world, and be waterproof and super protective of all your stuff and be near weightless on your back and have 7000 pockets for all your little odds and ends, this ain\'t it. My husband is appalled at this bag, because his backpack has those 7000 dedicated pockets for odds and ends and he can\'t fathom life without that level of organization. And maybe my "forever bag" will have that. But for a cheap backpack for once in a while use, or the casual commuter, or someone who just wants to feel out using a backpack as a work bag rather than a more traditional shoulder bag, this is a great buy.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States November 18, 2019', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Second Purchase', 'author': 'Adolph Dixon', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I purchase this backpack almost two years ago. For the price this was a very good buy. The previous purchase held up pretty good. Has minor tears in the front inside pocket. Otherwise, looks as good as new.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 11, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Awesome value and good build quality!', 'author': 'Amazon Customer', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Great all around laptop bag that includes lots of extra space for your day to day “stuff”. Fits my Surface Laptop perfectly and has decent padding to help protect from accidental drops.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 21, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': "5.0 out of 5 stars Slim, Stylish, and Super Travel-Friendly - Best Backpack I've Ever Owned!", 'author': 'Alexander D. Dragu', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Alright folks, buckle up 'cause I've got to tell you all about this fantastic backpack I bought last year. Honestly, it's been my trusty sidekick ever since, and I can't imagine life without it now! Let me give you the lowdown on why this backpack is the real MVP.First things first, I love how slim this backpack is. I mean, I'm always guilty of overstuffing my bags with random stuff I don't need (guilty as charged!). But this backpack has been like my personal Marie Kondo, helping me declutter and carry only the essentials. And you know what? It's been a game-changer.Now, I've been taking this backpack with me on all my travels, and it's been an absolute dream. Flying with it is a walk in the park 'cause it's small enough that TSA never gives me any grief, and it fits snugly under the seat in front of me. No more awkwardly trying to shove an oversized bag into the overhead compartment, thank goodness!One thing I really appreciate about this backpack is how comfy it is to carry around all day. I've had my fair share of bags that left my shoulders and back aching by the end of the day, but not this one! It's like the backpack equivalent of a cozy hug, I'm telling ya!Now let's talk pockets. You know how some bags have a gazillion compartments and you can never find what you're looking for? Well, not with this backpack! It's got just the right amount of pockets, making it super easy to find everything I need. No more endless searching for that one pen or my headphones. It's like the backpack gods finally heard my prayers!There is just one teeny-tiny downside to this otherwise perfect bag. If you're like me and sometimes can't help but cram too much stuff in there, you might risk tearing the threads in the main compartment at the top. But I've learned my lesson and started being more mindful about what I pack. So really, it's more on me than the bag itself, right?In conclusion, considering the price, this backpack is hands down the best one I've ever had the pleasure of owning. It's stylish, slim, comfy, and easy to use – everything I could ask for in a backpack! So if you're on the hunt for the perfect backpack for your daily grind or your globetrotting adventures, look no further. This is the one, my friends! Trust me, you won't regret it!Here's a poem I wrote just for this:There once was a backpack, so slim and so fine,It changed how I traveled and made my days shine,I bought it last year, and it's now my best friend,Helping me carry my stuff 'round the bend.Its slimness, a blessing, I've come to embrace,No longer weighed down by stuff, I feel grace,It's been on my back on adventures afar,And breezing through TSA, we've raised the bar!This backpack of mine, it's a snug little hug,Comfort all day, no more shoulders to shrug,It's got just the pockets I need, oh so nifty,Finding my things now, so easy and swift-y!But listen up, folks, there's a lesson I've learned,From stuffing it full, some threads I have churned,So be mindful, dear friends, of what you pack in,Too much and you'll find, that it's quite a sin.For the price, it's a steal, this bag oh so grand,The best backpack ever, in all of the land,So if you need something slim, comfy, and fun,Look no further, my friend, this bag's the home run!Humor and rhyme, in this tale of my sack,Trust me, you'll love it, it's got your back!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States April 17, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Perfect, Compact, Inconspicuous looking backpack', 'author': 'Burvy', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'This backpack fits all of my stuff in it perfectly, and no space looks wasted. When it\'s full, it gives just the compact sleek look I was looking for, without all the sagging that bigger backpacks usually offer me. This backpack is also immensely more portable, but you may want to take a bit more care if you keep electronics inside because there is very minimal padding to save space. All in all, this backpack is very "normal" looking, it won\'t draw many eyes to you because it doesn\'t look saggy or attention grabbing like bigger backpacks do.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 17, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': "5.0 out of 5 stars It's What You Pay For", 'author': 'Michael', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Just bought after buying a new pc using it to keep my old one and all the parts in one place. I have the high-end leno bag and you get what you pay for throughout their product line. This model would be great for a kis school back , but I need something a little bigger and for durably padded for my totting on pcs.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 7, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Excellent backpack for laptop handle.', 'author': 'Daniel Polanco', 'rating': 4, 'content': "Excellent backpack for laptop handle, bit it can't be used in outdoors travels.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 27, 2024', 'is_verified': True}]

Wonderful bargain but light to medium load capabilities.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States October 5, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Good Solid Canvas Backpack - Can be Easily Painted with Acrylic Paints if you Want it Customized', 'author': 'K. Chan', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I bought two of these backpacks for my two elementary school kids and they are perfect for what they require. The backpacks themselves are durable and just the right size for the kids. I would say they are comparable to other canvas type backpacks out there that are 2-3 times the cost. The backpacks can easily hold a binder, a notebook, a pencil case, a lunch, a few books, and a sweater with room to spare - keeping in mind that this is for elementary school kids again...our kids are young so they don\'t carry much at all. If you\'re planning on carrying a High School load of text books, you may want to consider getting the larger sized backpack. The stitching at the seams is durable and we\'ve had no issues with torn seams or canvas. The zipper also runs very smoothly.Because the backpacks are solid in color, we ended up decorating the backpacks with acrylic paint to spice things up. The paint dries well on the canvas, looks vibrant, and give the backpack an extra protective coat. If you\'re considering drawing on the backpack with Sharpie, keep in mind that Sharpie on canvas tends to bleed a bit, and won\'t look quite as vibrant. You can also remove the "Everest" label very easily if you don\'t want the tab there and clean the material underneath with a toothbrush and stain stick - the coloring under the label will come right off. If you want a good glossy finish, you can also finish the painting with a clear acrylic coat. We did Lego Avengers on one bag and Japanimation Hello Kitty on the other - the kids love their backpacks!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States August 15, 2014', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Bought for my grandson', 'author': 'Athena Moore', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I bought this bookbag for the grandson because of the cost. title: Della Gao Large Anti-Theft Laptop Backpack with USB Charging Port for 17-Inch Laptops
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Inexpensive, but long lasting and durable!', 'author': 'Dr. Sean Henry', 'rating': 5, 'content': "This is my second Della Gao Travel Laptop Backpack, replacing an older identical one. And the only reason I am replacing the older one is because it is getting grungy and starting to stink after more than 2 years of daily use waking to work, often with a packed lunches inside. I probably could have washed it after detaching the USB charger, but at such a very reasonable price, I decided to get a new one just like it!I have used the backpack for traveling with my heavy 17-inch laptop, too. It is very sturdy and does not stretch the stitches apart at the shoulder straps like another brand of laptop backpack I once had. The back of the outermost laptop compartment is well padded, which protects the laptop and also makes the backpack more comfortable to wear. I have not had the opportunity to use the USB charging port, but I'm glad it's there, just in case.I really like the mesh outer pockets on both sides of the backpack for my keys and smartphone when I'm walking (I walk in a low crime area). The pockets would be good for a water bottle or small thermos, too. The red and white tabs on the backpack are highly reflective for safety after dark. It's water resistance keeps things dry when I am walking in the rain.I've had many backpacks over the years, and except for an expensive leather backpack I had back in the 1990s, this Della Gao Travel Laptop Backpack is my favorite!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States November 10, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great product', 'author': 'Amazon Customer', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'All the pockets are easy to access and tons of storage space.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 22, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great for. That isn\'t really a big con to me, so I gave this product a 4 star because in every other way I\'m satisfied so far :)', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States September 18, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Fits MacBook Pro 15 + sleeve, lots of room for more stuff, good for day-to-day travel, air carry-on.', 'author': 'the kat', 'rating': 5, 'content': '15.6", PURPLEi JUST received this, so this is based on first impressions:TLDR:If i need to replace due to anything other than catastrophic failure, i would get this again.Paid: $29.99 USD. Free Shipping (Amazon Prime). Received in two days.Easily holds MBP 15" with a protective sleeve, plus several notebooks (paper or digital) and/or binders, charger(s), a light-weight jacket or sweater, miscellaneous small personal stuff, orthe computer/notebook, charger(s), overnight change of clothes, a small makeup bag,Good for day-to-day commuter use, or as personal item or carry-on for air travel.Worth the price (so far).OVERALL:i wouldnʻt ask this to protect a laptop from a 5-6ʻ fall off your shoulder onto a hard surface, like just dropping the backpack onto a hard floor - if the computer survived more than a couple of times, iʻd consider the aluminum-silicon gods being extra generous. However, if you fell off your bike while wearing it, and you absorbed part of the fall, i think your laptop and backpack might come out ok. (yeah, iʻve gone through that before, donʻt want to test this back pack with that, though.) Good capacity and access. Construction should stand up to light-moderate use (up to 8-10 lb).DETAILS:Outer shell:medium duty polyester knit fabric: the manufacturer/vendor answering a question says it is 900 denier; not outback trekking material, but good enough for around-town commuter use. reported as water resistant, feels like it, but i donʻt plan to deliberately test it just yet. The front, bottom, and back outer shell is lined with a thin padding that feels like maybe 1/8" poly-something, the kind of material used for wrapping light-weight things for packing, The back of the pack has an additional foam padding, not super thick, adds a bit of protection for contents, but possibly more for providing wearer comfort. Construction feels adequate for carrying a computer and a few light things (notebooks, jacket, etc.) up to about 8-10 lbs to me.Interior lining:medium-light weight polyester. The entire backpack is lined and divided with this material. Feels as though it too might be water resistant, although, again, iʻm not testing it.zippers: medium duty(?) nylon. one very light-duty combination padlock included.shoulder straps: 2 1/4" wide seam-to-seam, padding 2" wide.hand strap (top): 7 1ʻ2" long, 1" wide, 3/8" thick (thick medium dense material core, like urethane foam?)luggage cart strap: on the back surface of the backpack, allows it to be plunked onto the top of rolling luggage by the rolling luggage handle, and prevented from falling off.reflector tabs: 1/2" x 3/4" (4x), 1" x 3/4" (1x)Side Pockets: 6" deep, 4 3/4" wide, 3/8" wide elastic cuff expands from 5" to ~7". Synthetic (Poly or Nylon?) mesh, 3/8" elastic opening cuff. Holds a 3 1/4" wide water bottleMain cargo section:interior dimensions:5 3/4" deep at base, tapering to 3 1/12" at top.12" wide at base, a mild taper to 11 3/4" at the top of the laptop pocket, and the last 1 1/4" of height tapers from 10 1/2" to 7" width.17 3/4ʻ tall.Lots of room for laptop, and a two inch 3-ring binder, or one or two textbooks, notebooks, etc. Someone in the questions section of the reviews said this can hold a 5" binder: it probably could hold a laptop and that,, but i suspect not much else. Maybe the 17" or the 18.4" models have deeper capacity.laptop pocket is a 1" deep bellows- or safari style pocket, so it isnʻt stretched to accomodate even my MacBook Pro 15ʻ Unibody in padded sleeve. The pocket is 12" tall, so the entire laptop fits in the pocket. The inner-facing side of the pocket is lightly padded, so it will last longer, and protect the computer somewhat from scratching or denting by any hard objects you might have in the main cargo section of the backpack.Pass through for USB and headphone cables. Pass-through is NOT watertight! rubber strain relief around the holes in the fabric, but no rain deflector like on the larger model of backpack. moisture can get in, depending on how heavy the rain or spill is.Secondary section:interior dimensions1 7/8" deep at base, tapering to 1 1/4" at top11" wide at base, tapering to 9" near the top15" tall at the zipperpatch pockets, main one is 5" deep, 9" height to zipper, sewn onto divider wall between secondary compartment and main cargo compartment.Organizer compartment11" at base, tapering to 9" at top15" tallzipper opening reaches to 10" height.flat profileEssentially, a patch pocket with a zipper opening, the front surface is the padded/lined shell, the inner side the same interior lining as everything else.three patch-style credit card-sized RFID pockets. not tested for effectiveness yet.Should be able to tuck a notebook in this space, but probably not anything wider than a 3/4" 3-ring binder, unless you donʻt mind swiping volume from the other compartments.WHAT I LIKE:PROTECTION:MOST of the the outer shell is padded (albeit lightly). It should protect from casual bumps agains desks, shelves, etc.CAPACITY:The shell feels like it will stand up to day-to-day light-to medium duty use. Construction is adequate for carrying about 10-12 pounds. More than that would probably start to strain seams, handles, and zippers.LOTS of capacity for a 15" laptop (even the MacBook Pro Unibody) in a foam sleeve, plus charger, note pads (paper or digital), one or two medium to large books, a light jacket.For air travel, I can probably squeeze my purse inside and use the back pack as my "personal item". Even stuffed to capacity, this probably will fit under most airline seats.ACCESSIBILITY:The Main and Secondary compartments have wide openings: the Main compartment opens 12" from the top on both sides (double zipper), the Secondary opens 8" from the top, also double zipper. The front organizer pocket easily holds my iPad 2021 in its sleeve, so pulling it out at airport security is no problem. Depending on how much stuff i have packed, the laptop should easily come out and go back into its pocket as well.ORGANIZATION:Each of the compartments (Main, Secondary, Organizer) is large enough to accommodate a notebook/notepad. Organizing paper documents is much easier with this rather than a single compartment or with small compartments.oh yeah, the PURPLE is awesome.WHAT I WISH:MORE PADDING:The sides and top of the backpack are not padded - just the outer shell and inner lining. I wish these were padded, to help cushion falls/drops/bumps. iʻm kind of klutzy at times, and so every bit of protection helps.The separations between compartments are made of the interior lining fabric only; i wish these were also padded, as they would add protection and also give more body to the Secondary and Organizer compartments.The shoulder straps have thin padding (1/8"?): because they are 2" wide, it should mitigate the cutting into my shoulders, but i tend to overload my backpack, so extra padding is always welcome.STRONGER ZIPPERS: the bane of my existence. i hope these zippers last the two years i want to get out of this backpack. not super confident, but if i donʻt overload it, i might make it.BIGGER/DEEPER SIDE POCKET with drawstring closure: i carry 3 1/4" dia. 1 liter bottles with insulation; the side pockets just fit them, without insulating pouch, while they do fit, the 6" depth and elastic cuff seem a bit limited for larger water bottles. I guess itʻs a trade-off, since the pockets are just deep enough so that they donʻt interfere with the main compartment zippers.Cord Passthrough unnecessary: for me, putting holes in a backpack doesnʻt make sense - itʻs just somewhere for moisture to get in. Headsets are going Bluetooth, and if you need to charge your handheld device, itʻs probably at the point where you shouldnʻt be using it anyway, and can just put it in the backpack to charge with whatever portable recharger you carry with you.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States May 16, 2022', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great', 'author': 'Justin A Jones', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I use this for work and can fit everything I need in it. Great amount of pockets inside and the bag is very comfortable and very durable from rough treatment.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 9, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Almost perfect but no laptop cushioning', 'author': 'Ed.Doc99', 'rating': 4, 'content': "This backpack is GREAT!! I got it for its dimensions for an international travel carryon to maximize cubic inches (AerLingus, to be exact).I stuffed it full, and along with my medium sized Lug bag, I could’ve gone full carryon/no checked baggage if I’d been just a bit more disciplined because they’re really is a TON of room in this backpack.My only complaints are:1. There are only about two internal pockets that have zippers. I expected more of those.2. The laptop storage area, while ample and well-designed in that it has a wide elastic strap with Velcro at the end, has ZERO padding between the laptop and the exterior or bottom of the backpack. Not a problem while you’re wearing it, but *very* concerning if you’re stowing this in overhead bins on airplanes or public transit with your precious laptop inside. **So you’ll want to get a very protective laptop sleeve to use inside this backpack.**3. No anti-theft technology other than double zippers that have holes large enough to accept luggage locks. I did get TSA-approved combination locks elsewhere on Amazon, and they’ve been great.4. The chest strap is bizarre because it’s not long enough to go across an adult human’s chest. It’s only about seven inches long. That’s confusing. Maybe I’m misunderstanding something there.The clamshell feature for the electronics area *might* be pointless because the backpack is so tall. I say “might” because perhaps you’ll have a more favorable experience than mine, below:AerLingus, as of July 2023, does not have a contract with TSA 🤔, so I couldn’t use my KTN to get through security faster. 🤯 🤷\u200d♀️ Thus, I had to put this backpack in a security bin and remove my laptop, portable monitor, and Kindle.I asked if I could just unzip it all the way and lie it flat Like a clamshell, but the security agent kindly pointed out that when opened all the way, this backpack extends beyond the boundaries of the (quite large) security bin, so he said I indeed had to remove all my electronics.I don’t know if every agent would've said that, but that was my experience this time.I do understand that to include the upgrades listed here that I’d like to see, it would cost a lot more for this backpack. So, for the money, I’m pretty satisfied with this purchase, especially because it has a TON of room and double zippers that accept luggage locks for all the outer compartments. (My Lug bag, while much more stylish, has zippers that do not accept luggage locks; the holes in the zipper pulls are way too small! 😥)Given that this backpack has no other anti-theft technology, I’ll probably be investing in a PacSafe bag next. HOWEVER, this backpack has worked out very well for functionality.I got it just a couple of days before my trip, so it really helped me out in a pinch. If you’re on a budget and/or need it super fast, then this is a great choice!Btw, my weight limit was 10kg, and this could’ve held a lot more than that. However, I’m not strong enough to carry around that much weight all day. So bigger isn’t always better.After arriving at my destination and unpacking, I used this backpack for grocery shopping in areas that have public transit and we didn’t rent a car. This backpack was perfect for that! Just make sure to still put most food items, such as dairy, sugary items, sauces, powders/flour, and anything else that would be difficult to clean into plastic grocery bags before putting them into your backpack. This way, in case anything leaks, your investment will be protected and you won’t smell gross for the rest of your trip!I really do recommend this backpack if you need something fast, need a 10 kg bag for travel to the UK and want to maximize your cubic inches of space, after winning to purchase a separate, very cushioning laptop sleeve, want to make it fast and easy to remove your electronics at security if needed, and/or you’re on a budget.If you can afford to spend $50+ more, you might want to look elsewhere.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States July 10, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Good quality', 'author': 'Karen M.', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I absolutely love this back pack. title: ULANZI BP10 Hardshell Camera Backpack, Professional Waterproof Photography Camera Case Anti Theft Travel for Photographers Unisex Drone DSLR Mirrorless Camera Lens Tripod Holder 17'' Laptop Black 35L
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Finally! An affordable quality bag for my gear!', 'author': 'Christopher', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I\'ve been looking for a bag that\'s not ridiculously overpriced, that\'s durable, and has room for more gear than I usually carry. I\'m easily able to fit a 5D Mark IV with a 70-200 2.8 II attached, a 6D Mark II with a 24-70 2.8 II attached, a 100mm 2.8 L Macro, a 50mm 1.8, 24-105 F4 II, 35mm 1.4 II, 16-35mm F4 inside, and my Godox V860 III fits in the front pouch with room to spare. I haven\'t even expanded the bag to gain its additional 10L of space, but that\'ll come in handy for traveling when I need to pack clothes and other essentials. There are also a ton of pockets for memory cards, card readers, batteries, etc. All for under $150 USD. The outer materials of the bag are soft but durable, and the fabrics inside are all soft to the touch but well made. The velcro tabs are also easy to configure how I need them, and I still have a couple of pieces left over. The belt attachment that comes with the bag fits me, even though I\'m a big guy (6\'4" and 365lbs).I don\'t often travel with this much gear, but I have an out of state wedding I\'m going to be photographing in April and I needed a bag that fits extra gear, and can be taken as a carry on. Overall, VERY impressed with this new bag. This is also my first purchase of a Ulanzi product, so I\'ll have to check some of their other stuff out now as well. With everything I have loaded so far, the total weight of the bag is at 22.7 lbs.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 31, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Everything but the kitchen sink fits.', 'author': 'gail duckworth', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'In preparation for an African Safari coming up in June, I found myself in need of a larger camera backpack. After many hours spent researching what was out there, I settled on the Ulanzi bp10 hardshell camera backpack 35l. It seems to be very well made, has plenty of room for all my gear, is comfortable on my back, and most importantly there is a zippered access panel on both sides. Although I have only had this backpack for a week, as of right now, I have no complaints and would definitely recommend it.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 22, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '2.0 out of 5 stars Zippers do not hold up', 'author': 'Jordan Johnson', 'rating': 2, 'content': 'Zippers are not built to last. Coming from a langly bag that has very sturdy zippers I was shocked. You will be replacing them in 2 years be warned!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 22, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': "4.0 out of 5 stars It's a very well designed bag but has a flaw I don't think it will last years of hard use.", 'author': 'Jimmy Ji', 'rating': 4, 'content': "This bag is hard to fully recommend, but I don't think it's a bad bag.I love the look and design and all the compartments and pockets are amazing.It uses it's space really well and has more pockets than most other bags if that is important to you.The expansion from 25l to 35l is cool but also a problem since you sacrifice that extra 10l as a separate compartment instead of in the main compartment. So the depth of where you will put your camera and lenses could be deeper if it wasn't split into 2 compartments but you actually don't have that much as you would think. I am using small/medium lenses in my photos. Something like a 24-105 would not be flush with the main compartment. (But you could still zip it up)I thought I could live with the PU leather, but if you are like me and throw your bag around then I do not think the material will last.What I hate the most about this bag is that you have to open it face down backup so that means the front is on whatever the ground surface is. I wish there was at least another hard cover on the other front pouch to take the damage and force , but since there isn't I can see the front bottom pouch getting shredded over time.Also the fact you have to open the main compartment with the front down mean you have to keep zipping it up to then flip back around to get to the front pockets. This bag slowed me down on a recent shoot a lotlIf you swing the backpack around to the front to grab the camera on one of the side zippers that go to the main compartment the camera will be upside down because of that reason that it has to open face down.I love the included waist strap that you can attach or take off. I had to tuck the clip straps underneath the pockets since I did not want it dangling and honestly it works great. Not sure if it was designed for that.I can recommend this if you don't think you will abuse your backpack, but I am so run and gun the backpack will get pushed to it's limits though I think $150 is a bit high.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 20, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': 'se ve muy bien', 'author': 'javier', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'apenas la usare pero se ve de muy buena calidad, estaba buscanbdo una mochila asi desde hace tiempo y otras de 2500 o menos se rompian facil por el peso que cargo en la mochila pero esta s eve que resistira mucho y es muy amplia', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in Mexico January 5, 2024', 'is_verified': True}]

The ripped water bottle holders on the side being ripped so easily could have been made with higher quality material or stitching.I think it's a nice looking backpack.
